# Rust Conventions

## Error Handling

- Never use `.unwrap()` or `.expect()` in non-test code unless the invariant is provably guaranteed. Prefer `?` propagation or explicit error handling.
- Use `.unwrap()` and `.expect()` freely in test code for clarity.
- Return `Result` or `Option` from functions that can fail.

## Arithmetic Safety

- Use `saturating_sub`, `saturating_add`, `checked_mul`, etc. for counters and indices that could overflow or underflow.
- Never rely on wrapping arithmetic unless intentional.

## Naming

- Types and traits: `PascalCase`
- Functions, methods, variables: `snake_case`
- Constants: `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE`
- Prefer descriptive names. Abbreviations are acceptable when they are domain-standard (e.g., `pct`, `cpu`, `irq`).

## Ownership and Borrowing

- Prefer borrowing (`&T`, `&mut T`) over cloning unless ownership transfer is required.
- Use `&str` in function parameters instead of `String` when the function doesn't need ownership.
- Avoid unnecessary `clone()` calls — they are a code smell unless justified.

## Structure

- Keep `main.rs` thin — it should only contain setup, teardown, and the main loop. Push all testable logic into library modules.
- One concern per module. Data parsing in `cpu.rs`, rendering in `ui.rs`, etc.
- Mark items `pub` only when needed by other modules. Default to private visibility.

## Style

- No dead code — remove unused functions, imports, and variables.
- No commented-out code in committed code.
- Prefer iterators and combinators (`.map()`, `.filter()`, `.collect()`) over manual loops when they improve clarity.
- Use `match` over chains of `if/else if` when matching on enums or discrete values.
- Destructure structs and tuples when it improves readability.

## Performance

- Prefer `&str` over `String` for read-only string operations.
- Use `String::with_capacity()` when building strings of known or estimable size.
- Avoid allocations in hot loops (the 1-second render cycle). Pre-allocate buffers and reuse them.

## Dependencies

- Minimal external crates. Currently only `crossterm` is allowed.
- Read system data from `/proc/` and `/sys/` directly — no system monitoring crates.
- Justify any new dependency before adding it.
